[In February 2014, there were reports of a polio-like illness in approximately 20 children since the fall of 2012. Descriptions of the illness included "severe weakness or paralysis, which strikes rapidly -- sometimes after a mild respiratory illness. Scans of the patients' spinal cords show patterns of damage similar to that found in polio sufferers...." -- Basically the same as described in cases in Colorado reported above. At the time there was mention that 2 of 5 children evaluated at Stanford University Medical Center had evidence of infection with enterovirus 68 (the virus was recovered from stool specimens; see Polio-like illness - USA: (CA) enterovirus 68 susp, RFI 20140224.2296126).

Non-polio enteroviruses (NPEVs) have been associated with polio-like paralytic disease. As part of the global polio eradication initiative, stool specimens are to be collected and sent for virus isolation on all cases of acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) that are identified. This massive laboratory-supported effort has led to the identification of many non-polio enteroviruses associated with AFP (see references listed below for a representative sampling of the types of viruses associated with AFP). Of these NPEVs, EV71 has been most notably associated with paralytic disease, and more recently, sub-genogroup C4a was associated with AFP in Australia (see ProMED-mail Human enterovirus 71 - Australia: sub-genogroup C4a, acute flaccid paralysis 20130526.1738087). While EV68 has been anecdotally associated with AFP, it has been identified as a cause of severe respiratory disease (see ProMED-mail Human enterovirus 68 - novel pathogen, worldwide 20110929.2945 with a Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR) article summarizing the reports of respiratory illness associated with EV68). In late August 2014, there were reports of severe respiratory illness in children in Missouri (see ProMED-mail Human enterovirus 68 - USA: (Kansas City, MO) 20140830.2737051), followed by reports of enterovirus 68 activity with severe respiratory illness in other Midwest states, then in the Northeast and in Canada. As of 24 Sep 2014 there have been a total of 220 confirmed cases of EV-D68 infection in 32 states.

In 2003 and 2005 there were a cumulative total of 17 individuals with neurologic symptoms associated with EV71 infection in Colorado, including 2 presenting with AFP (see https://idsa.confex.com/idsa/2006/webprogram/Paper22621.html for details of this cluster presented as a poster at the IDSA Pediatrics 1 poster session on 13 Oct 2006: Perez-Velez C, Robinson C, McFarland E, et al: Outbreaks of paralytic enterovirus 71 disease in Colorado).

Based on the clusters reported in California earlier this year (covering an 18-month period preceding February 2014) and the cluster of 9 additional cases mentioned above, and the concurrent large outbreak of EV-D68 respiratory illness, CDC has issued an alert to all states to report similar cases of "acute neurologic illness with focal limb weakness of unknown etiology in children". The case definition is: Patients 21 years of age or younger, with an acute onset of focal limb weakness occurring on or after 1 Aug 2014, and an MRI showing a spinal cord lesion largely restricted to gray matter.

More information on these cases would be greatly appreciated.

For a map showing the location of Colorado in the USA, see https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2809908,209.

